So you are bundling your code with webpack with typescript and wants to use a cdn for axios?

Seems like that `externals` is a better approach.

https://webpack.js.org/configuration/externals/

With that, you can install axios with npm in your project, use it normally and when webpack transpiles it, it will use the cdn.

```html
<!-- index.html -->
<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/axios/dist/axios.min.js"></script>
```

```js
// webpack.config.js
module.exports = {
  // ...
  externals: {
    axios: 'axios'
  }
}
```

```ts
// some-file.ts
import axios from 'axios';

const request = axios.get('url');
```

Are you sure that this is not working? I setup a simple example in my browser and it is working. Have you tried to put a `console.log('here')` at the top of the interceptor to test it?

In your example, you returned `response.data`, but the correct usage is to return the entire `response`. Maybe this is the problem.

```js
axios.interceptors.request.use((config) => {
  // stuff
  return config;
})

axios.interceptors.response.use((response) => {
  // stuff
  return response; // not response.data
})
```

