For use cases that requires handling on the client side, we can simply implement our own template for our use case.

Consider the following code for unhandled 404 content, the client expects a json response from a file path `integrations.json`. If the file does not exist, the server would have returned an HTML with status code of 200 which would pass through axios and we get HTML as content.

Using a one-off axios interceptor as a solution to solve the issue worked in this case because I was able to intercept the incoming response and act accordingly. Maybe you can `set it up the interceptor as per request basis` just like I did?

```js
// Axios interceptor: Reject HTML response
// Allow response as long as content-type contains application/json
// Caveat: Server must return the correct content-type response
const interceptor = axios.interceptors.response.use(response => {
    return response.headers['content-type'].includes('application/json')
        ? response
        : Promise.reject(response);
}, error => Promise.reject(error));

// Get integrations json
axios.get(`${window.location.origin}/js/integrations/integrations.json`)
    .then((response) => {
            this.loading = false
            this.integrations = response.data

            // remove interceptor after processing data
            axios.interceptors.response.eject(interceptor);
        }
    )
    .catch((error) => {
        console.warn(error)
        this.loading = false
    });
```

After a couple of hours of digging the web for a solution, I came to realize that cookies are client base and live in the browser so what I am trying to do won't work because my client doesn't live in the browser. so I came up with this simple solution of registering the cookies manually.
```
const sender = axios.create({
    baseURL: process.env.API_BASE_URL
});

export default async function SendApiRequest(url, method = "get", params = undefined) {
    try {
        axios.defaults.withCredentials = true;
        const res = await sender[method](`${url}`, params);
        if(res.headers["set-cookie"]){
            const [cookie] = res.headers["set-cookie"];
            sender.defaults.headers.Cookie = cookie;
        }
        return res.data;
    } catch (err) {
        throw err;
    }
}
```

Axios doesn’t support true streaming in browsers; `resp.data` isn’t a `ReadableStream`. Use `fetch()` instead for Web Streams API support. Example:  

```javascript
const response = await fetch(url);
const reader = response.body.getReader();
while (true) {
  const { value, done } = await reader.read();
  if (done) break;
  console.log(value);
}
```  


### Update

It turns out Axios does support true streaming, but only when using the fetch adapter. The default XHR adapter buffers responses, so getReader() won’t work there.

To enable true streaming, explicitly set the fetch adapter like this:


```javascript
axios.get('https://your-streaming-url.com', {
  adapter: 'fetch',
  responseType: 'stream'
}).then(response => {
  if (response.data && response.data.getReader) {
    console.log("✅ ReadableStream received!");
    const reader = response.data.getReader();
    reader.read().then(({ value, done }) => {
      if (!done) console.log("Chunk received:", value);
    });
  } else {
    console.error("❌ Axios did not return a ReadableStream");
  }
}).catch(error => console.error("Streaming error:", error));

```

