Just set the header to `false` (https://codesandbox.io/p/sandbox/kind-rubin-ry0jex?file=%2Findex.js%3A6%2C1-10%2C4).
```js
const { data } = await axios.get("http://httpbin.org/get", {
  headers: {
    "User-Agent": false,
  },
});
```
OR
```js
axios.defaults.headers.common["User-Agent"] = false;
```
All headers are handled by the AxiosHeaders class and in the context of it:
- `null` value means do not include the header
- `false` means don't include the header and don't allow it to be set in upper chains (unless the `rewrite` option is explicitly set for the `headers.set` method)
```js
AxiosHeaders.concat({ x: 1, y: false }, { y: 123 }).toJSON();  // { x: '1' }

AxiosHeaders.concat({ x: 1, y: null }, { y: 123 }).toJSON();  // { x: '1', y: '123' }
```

The CORS error occurs due to how the server at `https://optimaxdev.github.io/perfect-match-iframe/products.csv` is configured. CORS, or Cross-Origin Resource Sharing, is a mechanism that uses additional HTTP headers to tell browsers to give a web application running at one origin (domain) permission to access selected resources from a server at a different origin.

When you add the headers to your axios request, the request becomes a "non-simple" request and the browser performs a preflight request before the actual request. This preflight request is an OPTIONS request that checks if the CORS protocol is understood and if the actual request is safe to send.

The problem is that the server must include the appropriate CORS headers in the response to the preflight request, indicating that it accepts the actual request. If the server doesn't include the necessary headers in its response, the browser denies the request and you get a CORS error. 

In your case, you are trying to add the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" header on the client side, but this is a response header, not a request header. It should be set by the server, not the client. You don't have control over the server at `https://optimaxdev.github.io/perfect-match-iframe/products.csv`, so you can't make it add this header to its responses.

You might be able to solve this problem by removing the "Access-Control-Allow-Origin" header from your axios request. But if you need to add headers to your request, and the server doesn't include the necessary CORS headers in its response to the preflight request, you might have to use a proxy server that adds these headers.

Here's an example of how you might modify your axios request:

```javascript
const { data } = await axios.get(
  `https://optimaxdev.github.io/perfect-match-iframe/products.csv`,
  {
    headers: {
      "Cache-Control": "no-cache",
      "Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded",
    },
  }
);
```

This might not fix your problem if the server doesn't handle preflight requests properly. In that case, you might need to use a proxy server. In that case, you may need to set up your call on a backend of your own and use your frontend API to call that instead.

