As this Github issue is Laravel specific, I'm assuming the commenters here (including myself) are facing this issue on our local environments due to the following in `lib/helpers/isURLSameOrigin.js` starting on line 55.

```javascript
return function isURLSameOrigin(requestURL) {
  const parsed = (utils.isString(requestURL)) ? resolveURL(requestURL) : requestURL;
  return (parsed.protocol === originURL.protocol &&
      parsed.host === originURL.host);
};
```

`url.host` includes a port whereas `url.hostname` does not. I'm not sure if we would want to consider the port a part of the origin or not, but this could be a fix that addresses these types of issues.

There is also a concern regarding subdomains. With this fix in place, no subdomain will be considered as the same origin even though cookies can be used across subdomains. This is a fairly serious issue.


I'm concerned that the security vulnerability fix had too many unintended consequences to remain in place. It changes assumed behavior of the underlying [XMLHttpRequest](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/XMLHttpRequest/withCredentials) settings. I think that informing the user of the risks would make much more sense in this scenario.

